Here’s a clear and complete guide to the most common Spring Boot REST API annotations for GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, etc., with runnable examples.

1. Controller-Level Annotations



Annotation
Purpose




@RestController
Marks a class as a REST API controller (combines @Controller + @ResponseBody).


@Controller
Marks a class as a Spring MVC controller (used for web pages or APIs).


@RequestMapping
Maps HTTP requests to handler methods or classes (can specify path + method).




2. HTTP Method Annotations



Annotation
HTTP Method
Usage




@GetMapping
GET
Retrieve data.


@PostMapping
POST
Create new data.


@PutMapping
PUT
Update existing data (replace).


@PatchMapping
PATCH
Partially update data.


@DeleteMapping
DELETE
Remove data.




3. Parameter Annotations



Annotation
Purpose




@PathVariable
Extracts values from the URL path.


@RequestParam
Extracts query parameters from the URL.


@RequestBody
Binds JSON/XML request body to a Java object.


@RequestHeader
Extracts HTTP header values.




4. Example Spring Boot REST API
Javapackage com.example.demo.controller;

import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.*;
import java.util.*;

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/users") // Base path for all endpoints
public class UserController {

    private Map<Integer, String> users = new HashMap<>();

    // GET - Retrieve all users
    @GetMapping
    public Map<Integer, String> getAllUsers() {
        return users;
    }

    // GET - Retrieve a user by ID
    @GetMapping("/{id}")
    public String getUserById(@PathVariable int id) {
        return users.getOrDefault(id, "User not found");
    }

    // POST - Create a new user
    @PostMapping
    public String createUser(@RequestParam int id, @RequestParam String name) {
        users.put(id, name);
        return "User created: " + name;
    }

    // PUT - Update an existing user
    @PutMapping("/{id}")
    public String updateUser(@PathVariable int id, @RequestParam String name) {
        if (users.containsKey(id)) {
            users.put(id, name);
            return "User updated: " + name;
        }
        return "User not found";
    }

    // DELETE - Remove a user
    @DeleteMapping("/{id}")
    public String deleteUser(@PathVariable int id) {
        if (users.remove(id) != null) {
            return "User deleted";
        }
        return "User not found";
    }
}


5. How It Works

@RestController → Makes the class a REST API controller.
@RequestMapping("/api/users") → All endpoints start with /api/users.
@GetMapping, @PostMapping, etc. → Map specific HTTP methods.
@PathVariable → Reads {id} from the URL.
@RequestParam → Reads query parameters like ?id=1&name=John.


✅ Tip:
If you want to handle JSON request bodies instead of query params, replace:
Javapublic String createUser(@RequestParam int id, @RequestParam String name)

with:
Javapublic String createUser(@RequestBody User user)

and create a User class.

